 authority? What in us responds to it? Is the mana that animates an Aboriginal ritual the same as the mana that energizes a revolutionary crowd, a consumer public, or an art encounter? At the intersection of anthropology and critical theory, The Mana of Mass Society brings recent conversations around affect, sovereignty, and emergence into creative contact with classic debates on religion, charisma, ideology, and aesthetics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAnthropologyxPhilosophy. 0aCritical theory. 0aMana. 0aMass media and anthropology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aaesthetics.  aaffect.  acharisma.  adialectics.  aimmanence.  amagic.  amana.  amimesis.  apublics.  asovereignty.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226436395423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226436395.jpg  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles